kshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Richmond, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Easby, North Yorkshire County, England":"Easby, North Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1165–Abt 1252":"about 1165–about 1252","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1190–1245":"1190–1245","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1130–1201":"1130–1201","1140–1226":"1140–1226","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1271":"1271","Abt 1252":"about 1252","1226":"1226","1158":"1158","1201":"1201","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"about 1165","1210":"1210","about 1210":"about 1210","1219":"1219","Manor of Croft, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Richmond Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Easby, North Yorkshire County, England":"Easby, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richmond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Richmond (North Yorkshire). The placename was probably transferred after the Norman Conquest from any of numerous places in France named with Old French <i>riche</i> ‘mighty, strong’ + <i>munt</i>, <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’. Richmond in southwest London received this name only in the reign of Henry VII, in honor of the king, who had been Earl of Richmond until he came to the throne, and is unlikely to be the source of this surname.","occasionally a variant of   Richman  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>. The two names were probably often confused.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Richman","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Richeman</i>, either from an unrecorded Old English <i>Rīcmann</i>, or from a pet form of <i>Richard</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-man</i>. The name was sometimes interchangeable with   Rickman  , especially in recent times.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>riche</i> ‘rich, powerful’ + <i>-man</i>. Compare   Rich  .","English: perhaps a variant of   Richmond  , or vice versa."]}]},{"name":"Roald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Old Norse <i>hróðr</i> ‘fame’ + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Roald de Richmond was born about 1165, in Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Alan FitzRoald de Richmond, was 37 and his mother, Olivia de Croft, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Lady Isabella de Rollo. He died about 1252, in Easby, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 89."},"et":{"Abt 1165–Abt 1252":"umbes 1165–umbes 1252","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1190–1245":"1190–1245","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1130–1201":"1130–1201","1140–1226":"1140–1226","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1271":"1271","Abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1226":"1226","1158":"1158","1201":"1201","1245":"1245","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1210":"1210","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1219":"1219","Manor of Croft, Yorkshire, E